---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const title = "Buying in a seller's market with a limited budget";
const description = "When demand exceeds supply and your budget is tight, strategy matters more than ever.";
---
<BaseLayout title={`${title} | BRIK`} description={description}>
  <section style="padding:28px 0 10px">
    <h2 style="font-size:30px;margin:0 0 10px;letter-spacing:-.4px">{title}</h2>
    <p style="margin:0 0 18px;color:var(--muted);max-width:82ch">{description}</p>
    <div class="card">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Scenario</h3>
      <p style="margin:0;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        Keisha has $22,000 saved and is pre-approved for $265,000. In her target market, well-priced homes are going under contract in 3-5 days with multiple offers. She's lost two offers already — once to a cash buyer and once to someone who went $18,000 over list. She's starting to think homeownership isn't possible on her budget. But she hasn't yet optimized her strategy for the market she's actually in.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div style="display:grid;gap:14px;grid-template-columns:repeat(12,1fr);margin-top:14px">
      <div class="card" style="grid-column:span 6">
        <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">What limited-budget buyers get wrong</h3>
        <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
          <li>Offering at or below list price in a market where homes sell above</li>
          <li>Long due diligence periods that signal hesitation</li>
          <li>Weak pre-approval letters with no lender credibility</li>
          <li>Targeting the most competitive price points instead of finding gaps</li>
          <li>Waiting for the perfect house instead of the right opportunity</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="grid-column:span 6">
        <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Strategies that work on a tight budget</h3>
        <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
          <li>Get fully underwritten pre-approval — not just a soft pull letter</li>
          <li>Target slightly older listings with higher DOM — less competition</li>
          <li>Offer strong terms: flexible close date, short due diligence</li>
          <li>Expand your geographic search by 10-15 minutes</li>
          <li>Consider properties that need cosmetic work — fewer buyers compete</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="margin-top:14px">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Things to consider</h3>
      <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        <li>What does your lender's pre-approval letter look like — does it signal strength or uncertainty?</li>
        <li>Are you targeting the most competitive segment of the market, or can you find a less contested price range?</li>
        <li>What terms matter most to the sellers you're losing to — price, timeline, certainty of close?</li>
        <li>Have you asked your agent to reach out to listing agents before offers are due to understand seller priorities?</li>
        <li>Is your agent experienced in competitive offer situations — do they know how to position you?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="margin-top:14px;background:rgba(255,255,255,.03)">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">BRIK takeaway</h3>
      <p style="margin:0;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        A limited budget in a seller's market requires strategy, not surrender. The buyers who win aren't always the ones with the most money — they're the ones with the strongest offers and the clearest communication. Know what sellers want and structure your offer to deliver it.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-top:12px">
        <a class="pill" href="/case-studies">Back to Case Studies</a>
        <a class="pill primary" href="/intake">Submit Intake</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>